Henderson Land, Ping An, Tencent: Hong Kong Stocks Preview

-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 
2011-05-12T00:33:32Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-12/henderson-land-ping-an-tencent-hong-kong-stocks-preview.html
The following companies may have
significant price changes in  Hong Kong  trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  fell 0.2 percent to 23,291.80. The Hang
Seng  China  Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H shares of
Chinese companies, gained 0.2 percent to 12,962.33.  Developers: Hong Kong will sell three land parcels in an
auction today that comes after home sales in April fell to the
lowest volume in two years following government measures to stem
surging prices.  Sun Hung Kai Properties Ltd. (16)  (16 HK), the world’s biggest
developer, rose 0.3 percent to HK$120.80.  Henderson Land Development Co. (12 HK), the builder
controlled by billionaire Lee Shau-kee, increased 0.2 percent to
HK$51.80.  Cheung Kong  (Holdings) Ltd. (1 HK), the developer
controlled by billionaire  Li Ka-shing , declined 1.9 percent to
HK$117.10.  Bank of Communications Co. (3328 HK): The lender signed a
cooperation agreement with Alibaba Group Holding Ltd. and will
start providing online banking services at the Internet
company’s Taobao online market place, Shanghai Daily said,
without saying where it got the information. Bank of
Communications declined 0.1 percent to HK$7.99.  China Overseas Land & Investment Ltd. (688)  (688 HK): The
developer controlled by the nation’s construction ministry said
property sales in April rose 68 percent from a year earlier to
HK$8.2 billion. The company’s property sales in the first four
months gained 50 percent to HK$28 billion, according to an e-
mailed statement. The stock increased 0.7 percent to HK$14.90.  China Pacific Insurance Group Co. (2601 HK): The nation’s
third-biggest insurer said life premiums for the first four
months were 39 billion yuan ($6 billion) and property premiums
were 21.7 billion yuan, according to a filing to the Shanghai
stock exchange. The shares gained 0.8 percent to HK$33.05.  Ping An Insurance Group Co. (2318 HK): China’s second-
largest insurer said its unit, Ping An Life Insurance Co. of
China Ltd., recorded premium income of 55.8 billion yuan for the
four months ended April 30, according to a statement to Hong
Kong’s stock exchange. Ping An dropped 0.4 percent to HK$82.65.  Tencent Holdings Ltd. (700)  (700 HK): China’s biggest Internet
company by revenue said first-quarter profit jumped 61 percent,
beating analysts’ estimates, after offering new online games to
boost sales. The stock was unchanged at HK$209.80.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Kana Nishizawa in Tokyo at 
 knishizawa5@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story: Nick Gentle at
